OZ map in tidyverse

library("oz")

Note that you can plot the map using the base R plotting functions like this:

oz()

But, if we want to plot it within the tidyverse we need to turn those points into a tibble. Lets do that

# get the lines for the map
oz_lines <- ozRegion()

oz_lines is a list. The third component is a list of x and y vectors that are long-lats for points along the oz coastline and states. (I hope).

So, we have to turn that into a tidy data frame much like you would get from map_data(). Which would look like:

head(map_data("usa"))

Attaching package: maps

The following object is masked from package:purrr:

    map

So, we can parse oz_lines out like this:

z <- oz_lines[[3]]
oz_tidy <- lapply(seq_along(z), function(i) {
  tibble(long = z[[i]]$x,
         lat = z[[i]]$y,
         group = i,
         order = 1:length(z[[i]]$x),
         region = as.character(i),
         subregion = NA)
  }) %>%
  bind_rows()

Now, plot that. We have to use geom_path rather than geom_polygon, because the things are stored as lines rather than as polygons.

ggplot(data = oz_tidy) + 
  geom_path(aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group)) + 
  coord_quickmap()

To see which pieces of the lines in the tibble correspond to which regions, we can color them by region:

ggplot(data = oz_tidy) + 
  geom_path(aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group, colour = factor(region))) + 
  coord_quickmap()
